@database preference_guide
@node Main "Preferences"
     Synopsis: Allows the user to alter some operations of DDBASE

     Shortcut x (LowerCase)


     @{"Animation    " link anim}
     @{"Sample Player" link sample}
     @{"Print        " link print}
     @{"Seperator    " link seper}
     @{"Calculate    " link calc}
     @{"Path         " link path}
     @{"Crunch       " link crunch}
     @{"Date         " link date}
     @{"Task Priority" link taskpri}
     @{"Save         " link save}
     @{"Use          " link use}
     @{"Use & Save   " link us}
@endnode


@node anim "Animations"

   ANIM      Select `l'.Enter the name of the ANIM player. It has to be
	     in the C directory. To use with a CLI use the `*' command.
	     IE. biganim * [other commands]

@endnode
@node sample "Sample Player"
   SAMPLE    Select 'R'.Enter the name of your prefered sample player
   PLAYER    ,dont forget to enter any parameters that the player may
	     require. IE dsound -m -w. It has to be in the C Directory.
	     If your sample player needs a CLI then use the `*' command.
	     IE. dsound * -m -w  .

@endnode
@node print "Print"
   PRINT     This option sets the page Length for output to a printer.
	     SEE the Print section.

@endnode
@node seper "Seperator"
   SEPERATOR This allows you to enter the field seperator.This is useful
	     when you are exporting or importing data from SuperBase.
	     {SuperBase ©Precision Software}

@endnode
@node calc "Calculate"
   CALCULATE Calculate when searching [=].Will open a window and display
	     all the selected fields.{See Calculations}

@endnode
@node path "Path"
   PATH      Set the Path for DDBASE.Keep all your files here.

@endnode
@node crunch "Crunch"
   CRUNCH    Will crunch any DDBASE #?.dat file thats saved.Needs
	     the command `crunch' to be in the c: directory.

@endnode
@node date "Date"
   DATE      Use DD/MM/YY or DD MMM YYYY (12/06/93 or 12 Jun 1993)

@endnode
@node taskpri "Taskpriority"
   TASKPRI   Alter the TaskPriority. (-10 to 20)

@endnode
@node save "Save"
   SAVE      This saves the preference settings.

@endnode
@node use "Use"
   USE	     This saves the preference settings to Ram:env/sys/.

@endnode
@node us "Use and Save"
   USE+SAVE  Take a guess at this one... Thats correct it saves the
	     Preference Settings to the current prefs (env:sys/) and to
	     prefs/Env-Archive/sys/.
@endnode


